The simple way to think about a credit default swap is that it is insurance=
 on a bond. If you own $1 million=C2=A0of the bonds of some company or gove=
rnment, you can buy $1 million of CDS to protect yourself; you pay some per=
iodic insurance premium for this protection. If the issuer defaults on its =
debt, you get made whole; you get your $1 million back.
When an issuer defaults on its debt, usually the debt is worth=C2=A0somethi=
ng:=C2=A0A company will go bankrupt and pay back its bonds at 20 or 40 cent=
s on the dollar or whatever, or a government will restructure its debt and =
give bondholders some value back. And so the way CDS works is basically tha=
t, when an issuer defaults, the CDS pays back 100 cents on the dollar=C2=A0=
minus=C2=A0the value of the bonds. If a company goes bankrupt and its bonds=
 recover 37 cents on the dollar, then its CDS will pay out 63 cents on the =
dollar. If you have $1 million of bonds plus $1 million of CDS, you will ge=
t back $370,000 on the bonds and $630,000 on the CDS and be fully insured.
Sometimes this works simply enough: A company has one set of bonds, it defa=
ults, they pay out 37 cents, the CDS pays the other 63 cents, easy. Sometim=
es, though, a company or government will have different bonds that get diff=
erent recoveries that are all covered by the same CDS contract. The CDS wil=
l pay out one amount, set by an auction and more or less corresponding to t=
he recovery of the=C2=A0worst=C2=A0(=E2=80=9Ccheapest-to-deliver=E2=80=9D) =
bond.
  [10]
=C2=A0And so if a company goes bankrupt and one bond gets 37 cents on the d=
ollar and another gets 41, the CDS will probably pay out about 63 cents on =
the dollar, and if you had one of the 41-cent bonds and hedged with CDS you=
 will get back 104 cents on the dollar, great.
To be clear, unlike in actual insurance, you don=E2=80=99t need to own the =
bonds to buy CDS. If you want to bet against a company=E2=80=99s credit, yo=
u can buy CDS on it, and then if it defaults you get the CDS payoff. (Peopl=
e get mad about this, but never mind; in financial markets buying CDS is a =
way to=C2=A0short=C2=A0bonds.) If=C2=A0the bonds pay off 37, then you get b=
ack 63; you never owned the bonds but that=E2=80=99s fine.
Notice that if you are a bond investor who bought CDS as a hedge, you don=
=E2=80=99t care very much about the bond recovery; if the recovery is X, yo=
u get X on the bonds and 1 - X on the CDS and it doesn=E2=80=99t matter wha=
t X is. If you bought CDS to short the bonds, though, you want the bond rec=
overy to be as low as possible, because you get paid 1 - X.
Where this becomes very fun is in the category of trade that is sometimes l=
oosely referred to as =E2=80=9Cmanufactured defaults.=E2=80=9D These trades=
 go something like this. Some company needs money. Some hedge fund owns a l=
ot of CDS on the company.
  [11]
=C2=A0The hedge fund goes to the company and says =E2=80=9Clook, it will he=
lp us out a lot if you default on your debt. Why don=E2=80=99t you just, li=
ke, miss the deadline for an interest payment by a week.
  [12]
=C2=A0Then you will be in default and our CDS will trigger and we=E2=80=99l=
l get paid. Then you go back and make the interest payment and nobody compl=
ains too much; you won=E2=80=99t go bankrupt or anything. And then we=E2=80=
=99ll have all this money from our CDS payoff, and we=E2=80=99ll write you =
a big check, and you=E2=80=99ll have more money too.=E2=80=9D
The mechanics are a bit more complicated,=C2=A0and people =E2=80=94=C2=A0ev=
en the pope! =E2=80=94=C2=A0get mad about this, but never mind that either.=
 The point I want to make here is just that there is a flaw in this logic, =
which is that if you manufacture a default at a company where=C2=A0everythi=
ng is otherwise fine, the bonds=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t lose much value, and so =
the CDS won=E2=80=99t pay off that much. The CDS will trigger, there=E2=80=
=99ll be an auction for the debt, people will be like =E2=80=9Cmeh this deb=
t is fine,=E2=80=9D the auction will clear at like 95 cents on the dollar, =
and the CDS will pay off like 5 cents.
And so there is a refinement on the manufactured-default trade, which is th=
at you also have to find, or manufacture, a bad=C2=A0bond. If some junk-rat=
ed-but-okay company has a lot of bonds that pay 12% interest and trade at 9=
9 cents on the dollar, and it manufactures a default, that doesn=E2=80=99t =
do its CDS holders much good. But if it has a 30-year bond with a 2% intere=
st rate that trades at 20 cents on the dollar, and=C2=A0it manufactures a d=
efault, then the CDS will pay off 80.
  [13]

Every so often the US government thinks about defaulting on its debt for no=
 particular reason; this is called the =E2=80=9Cdebt ceiling standoff.=E2=
=80=9D The somewhat surprising rule of thumb is that when there is a debt c=
eiling standoff =E2=80=94=C2=A0when the US government starts thinking about=
 defaulting on its debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0the price of US government debt goes=
=C2=A0up. The thinking is:
=09A US government default would be a bad destabilizing event in financial =
markets generally.=09When markets are bad and destabilized, there is a flig=
ht to quality; people want to buy safe assets.=09The safest assets are US g=
overnment debt, so the price of US government debt goes up.=09
Even in a US government default, US government debt will be safe, because t=
he government has plenty of money and is defaulting for no particular reaso=
n, and it will quickly fix the default and start paying its debts again.

So a US debt default would lead to panic, but not actually any significant =
impairment on the payments of, like, 30-year Treasury bonds. Which means th=
at the prices of those bonds will go up in the panic.
You can buy credit default swaps on US government debt, but historically th=
at has not been a great way to speculate on the debt ceiling standoff: If t=
he US government defaults, its bonds will=C2=A0trade to, like, 102 cents on=
 the dollar, and your CDS might trigger but won=E2=80=99t pay much.
But that is the thinking from a long period of declining interest rates, an=
d now things have changed. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Sujata Rao-Coverley, De=
nitsa Tsekova and Liz McCormick reported on Friday:

In what is a traditionally moribund corner of Wall Street, speculators are =
piling into a bet that once seemed unthinkable: that the US government will=
 default on its debts.=C2=A0
With the Treasury Department inching ever closer to running out of cash =E2=
=80=94 most estimates give it another=C2=A0few months=C2=A0=E2=80=94 tradin=
g in the derivatives, known as credit-default swaps, is growing. The amount=
 of money tied to the contracts, which will reward investors if the US miss=
es any payments, has increased roughly eight-fold since the start of the ye=
ar.
This isn=E2=80=99t the first time that a mini-mania around this trade has e=
rupted. There were episodes back in 2011, 2013, and to a lesser extent 2021=
. But this time, it all feels a bit different. =E2=80=A6 A quirk in the der=
ivatives market means they can take advantage of the rock-bottom prices on =
long-term US bonds to juice gains on the contracts should the US actually d=
efault. With some Treasuries recently trading below 60 cents on the dollar =
=E2=80=94 the result of the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s rapid-fire series of =
interest-rate hikes =E2=80=94 the potential payout could exceed 2,400%, acc=
ording to Bloomberg calculations.

Treasuries don=E2=80=99t trade below 60 cents on the dollar because people =
are worried about the credit risk of the US government. Treasuries trade be=
low 60 cents on the dollar because they are 30-year bonds issued in 2020 wi=
th interest rates of 1.25%, and now long-term interest rates are much highe=
r.
  [14]
=C2=A0If the US government defaulted this year, it is overwhelmingly likely=
 that holders of those bonds would get all of their money back, more or les=
s on schedule. But if the US government defaulted this year, credit default=
 swaps would trigger, and those bonds would sell for about 60 cents on the =
dollar. Which means that the CDS could pay out a lot.

