10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Wednesday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">First Republic</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s start with some bank accounting.=
 You=E2=80=99ve got a bank, its assets are $100 of loans, and its liabiliti=
es are $90 of deposits. Shareholders=E2=80=99 equity (assets minus liabilit=
ies) is $10, for a=C2=A0capital ratio (equity divided by assets) of 10%. Pr=
etty normal stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then the assets go down: The loans were worth =
$100, but then interest rates went up and now they are only worth $85. This=
 is less than $90, so the bank is insolvent, people panic, depositors get n=
ervous and the bank fails. It=C2=A0is seized by the Federal Deposit Insuran=
ce Corp., which quickly looks for a healthy bank to buy the failed one. Ide=
ally a buyer will take over the entire failed bank, buying $85 worth of loa=
ns and assuming $90 worth of deposits; borrowers and depositors will wake u=
p to find that they are now customers of the buyer bank, but everything els=
e is the same.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much should the buyer pay for this? The si=
mple math is $85 of assets minus $90 of assets equals negative $5: The buye=
r should pay negative $5, which means something like =E2=80=9Cthe FDIC give=
s the buyer $5 of cash to take over the failed bank,=E2=80=9D though it cou=
ld be more complicated.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that simple math is not quite right. If yo=
u pay negative $5 to take over a bank with $85 of assets and $90 of liabili=
ties, you effectively get a bank with $90 of assets,=C2=A0$90 of liabilitie=
s and $0 of shareholders=E2=80=99 equity. That doesn=E2=80=99t work. The ba=
nk, in the first paragraph, in the good times, did not have assets that equ=
aled its liabilities; it had assets that were $10 <em>more</em> than its li=
abilities. Banks are required =E2=80=94=C2=A0by regulation but also by comm=
on sense =E2=80=94=C2=A0to have <em>capital</em>, that is, shareholders=E2=
=80=99 equity,=C2=A0assets that exceed their liabilities. The buyer bank al=
so has to have assets that exceed its liabilities, to have capital against =
the assets that it buys. If it is buying $85 of loans, it will want to fund=
 them with no more than, say, $75 of liabilities. If it is=C2=A0assuming $9=
0 of deposits, it will have to pay, like, negative $15 for them, which mean=
s something like =E2=80=9Cthe FDIC gives the buyer $15 to take over the fai=
led bank.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a little weird. You could imagine a di=
fferent scenario. The FDIC seizes the bank and sells its loans to someone =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0a hedge fund, or a bank I guess =E2=80=94=C2=A0for $85, whic=
h is what they are worth. Then the FDIC just hands cash out to all the depo=
sitors at the failed bank, a total of $90, which is the amount of deposits.=
 At the end of the day there=E2=80=99s nothing left of the failed bank and =
the FDIC is out of pocket $5, which is less than $15.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The FDIC mostly doesn=E2=80=99t do this, thoug=
h, for a couple of reasons. One is that usually banks, even failed banks, h=
ave some franchise value: They have relationships and bankers and advisers =
that allow them to earn money, and the buying bank should want to pay somet=
hing for that. The value of a bank is not just its financial assets minus i=
ts liabilities; its actual business is worth something too. Selling it whol=
e can bring in more moneuy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another reason is that this approach is far mo=
re disruptive than keeping the bank open: Telling depositors =E2=80=9Cyour =
bank has vanished but here=E2=80=99s an envelope with your=C2=A0cash=E2=80=
=9D is worse, for general confidence in the banking system, than telling th=
em =E2=80=9Coh your bank got bought this weekend but everything is normal.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also there is a capital problem for the bankin=
g system as a whole: If the FDIC just hands out checks for $90 to all the d=
epositors, they will deposit those checks in other banks, which will then h=
ave $90 more of liabilities and will need some more capital as well. Sellin=
g the whole failed bank to another bank for $75 will cost the FDIC $15, but=
 it will=C2=A0<em>recapitalize the banking system</em>. The goal is to have=
 banks with ample capital, whose assets are worth much more than their liab=
ilities; the acute problem with a failed bank is that it has negative capit=
al; the solution is for someone to put in more money=C2=A0so that the syste=
m as a whole is well capitalized again. Sometimes the FDIC puts in the mone=
y.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This morning the FDIC <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDEvZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtc2VpemVkLWJ5L=
XJlZ3VsYXRvcnMtd2lsbC1iZS1zb2xkLXRvLWpwbW9yZ2FuP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDEyM19NT05F=
WVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI=
zMDUwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1b8e2d4f" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  seized First Republic Bank and sold it</a> to=C2=A0JPMorgan Chase=
 &amp; Co. My best guess at First Republic=E2=80=99s balance sheet as of, y=
ou know, yesterday would be something like this<a class=3D"footnote-index" =
href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: =
inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Assets:</em> Bonds worth about $30 billion; loans with a face value of =
about $173 billion but a market value of about $150 billion; cash of about =
$15 billion; other stuff worth about $9=C2=A0billion; for a total of about =
$227 billion at pre-deal accounting values=C2=A0but only $204 billion of ac=
tual value.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Liabilities:=C2=A0</em>Deposits of about $92 billion, of which $5 billi=
on came from JPMorgan and $25 billion came from a group of other big banks,=
 who <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.2584=
32/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcv=
YmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJlcHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9QkJ=
EMDUwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZX=
ImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBdc841e1b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">  put their money into First Republic</a> in March t=
o shore up confidence; the other $62 billion came from normal depositors. A=
bout $28 billion of advances from the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXd=
zL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjgvZmVkZXJhbC1ob21lLWxvYW4tYmFuay1zeXN0ZW0tYXZlcn=
RlZC1iaWdnZXItYmFua2luZy1jcmlzaXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX=
21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTAxJnV0bV9j=
YW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcd4461f3" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Feder=
al Home Loan Bank system</a>. About $93 billion of short-term borrowings fr=
om the Federal Reserve (discount window and Bank Term Funding Program).=C2=
=A0Those three liabilities =E2=80=94=C2=A0to depositors, to the FHLB, to th=
e Fed =E2=80=94=C2=A0really need to be paid back, and they add to about $21=
3=C2=A0billion. First Republic had some other liabilities, including a bit =
less than $1 billion of=C2=A0subordinated bonds, but let=E2=80=99s ignore t=
hose.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Equity:</em> The book value of First Republic=E2=80=99s equity yesterda=
y was something like $11 billion, including about $4 billion of preferred s=
tock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> The actual value of its equity was negative, though; its total assets =
of $204=C2=A0billion, at market value, were less than the $213 billion it o=
wed to depositors, the Fed and the FHLB, never mind its other creditors.</l=
i>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is, roughly, how the sale worked:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Assets:</em> JPMorgan bought all the loans and bonds, marking them at t=
heir market value, about $30 billion for the bonds and $150 billion for the=
 loans. It also bought $5 billion of other assets. And it attributed $1 bil=
lion to intangible assets, i.e. First Republic=E2=80=99s relationships and =
business.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s a total of about $186 billion of asset value. JPMo=
rgan left behind some assets, though, mainly the $15 billion of cash and=C2=
=A0about $4 billion of other stuff.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Liabilities:</em> JPMorgan assumed all of the deposits and FHLB advance=
s,=C2=A0plus another $2 billion of other liabilities, for a total of about =
$122 billion. (Of that, $5 billion was JPMorgan=E2=80=99s own deposit, whic=
h it will cancel.) The subordinated bonds <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanBtb3JnYW5jaGFzZS5=
jb20vY29udGVudC9kYW0vanBtYy9qcG1vcmdhbi1jaGFzZS1hbmQtY28vaW52ZXN0b3ItcmVsYX=
Rpb25zL2RvY3VtZW50cy9ldmVudHMvMjAyMy9qcG1vcmdhbi1jaGFzZS1hY3F1aXJlcy1zdWJzd=
GFudGlhbC1tYWpvcml0eS1vZi1hc3NldHMtYW5kLWFzc3VtZXMtY2VydGFpbi1saWFiaWxpdGll=
cy1vZi1maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYy1iYW5rLWNvbmZlcmVuY2UtY2FsbC0vSlBNb3JnYW5fQ2hhc2V=
fUHJlc2VudGF0aW9uLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB100ff7f2" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> got vap=
orized</a>: =E2=80=9CJPMorgan Chase did not assume First Republic Bank=E2=
=80=99s corporate debt or preferred stock.=E2=80=9D That effectively leaves=
 the shell of First Republic =E2=80=94=C2=A0now effectively owned by the FD=
IC in receivership =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the hook to pay back the roughly $93 b=
illion it borrowed from the Fed.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Payment:=C2=A0</em>JPMorgan will pay the FDIC $10.6 billion in cash now=
,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tran=
sparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> and another $50 billion in five years. It will pay (presumably low) in=
terest on that $50 billion.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a> So the FDIC will get about $60.6 billion to pay back the Fed, plus the=
 roughly $15 billion of cash and roughly $4 billion of other assets=C2=A0st=
ill left over at First Republic, for a total of about $80 billion.=C2=A0Fir=
st Republic owes the Fed about $93 billion, leaving the=C2=A0FDIC=E2=80=99s=
 insurance fund with a loss of $10=C2=A0billion or so. =E2=80=9CThe FDIC es=
timates that the cost to the Deposit Insurance Fund will be about $13 billi=
on,=E2=80=9D says <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmRpYy5nb3YvbmV3cy9wcmVzcy1yZWxlYXNlcy8yMDI=
zL3ByMjMwMzQuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11ddaa0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
