</a> that its bid =E2=80=9Cwas more appealing for the agency than the compe=
ting bids, which proposed breaking up First Republic or would have required=
 complex financial arrangements to fund its $100 billion of mortgages.=E2=
=80=9D And=C2=A0this is a pretty high bid: JPMorgan is paying $182.6 billio=
n, total, in cash and assumed liabilities, for a bank with about $180 billi=
on of loans and bonds at their current fair value; it is paying a bit extra=
 for the other assets and the intangible value of the First Republic franch=
ise. Still, it is acquiring the total package of assets for less than they =
are worth. That discount is required so that JPMorgan can properly capitali=
ze the assets, so that it can have enough capital against them. And that di=
scount is paid for by (1) First Republic=E2=80=99s shareholders, preferred =
stockholders and bondholders, who are getting wiped out and (2) the FDIC, w=
hich is also taking a loss on the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another point of the deal is that the FDIC is =
entering into loss-sharing agreements with JPMorgan, in which the FDIC will=
 agree to bear 80% of the credit losses on First Republic=E2=80=99s mortgag=
es and commercial loans. You can sort of imagine a simple story here: First=
 Republic is a failed bank, it made some bad choices, who knows if its loan=
s are toxic, JPMorgan had only a weekend to review them, it is not comforta=
ble taking the risk, so it demanded that the FDIC share in the risk.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is not really right. First Republic=
=E2=80=99s loans had famously=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>credit quality; First=
 Republic <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354=
.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDE=
vZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtcy1oaXN0b3J5LW9mLWp1bWJvLW1vcnRnYWdlcy1sZWQtYmFuay10by=
1mYWlsdXJlLXNhbGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpb=
CZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25l=
eXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB375a5b06" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  got itself in trouble=
</a> by making <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/313=
39354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
MtMDQtMTcvdGhlLXNlYy1jb21lcy1mb3ItYml0dHJleD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTAxMjNfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1=
MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB262645ee" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  low-interest mortgages to very rich people</a>, who will probably pay=
 back those loans. (But the loans have lost value due to the move in intere=
st rates.)=C2=A0And JPMorgan=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanBtb3JnYW5jaGFzZS5jb2=
0vY29udGVudC9kYW0vanBtYy9qcG1vcmdhbi1jaGFzZS1hbmQtY28vaW52ZXN0b3ItcmVsYXRpb=
25zL2RvY3VtZW50cy9ldmVudHMvMjAyMy9qcG1vcmdhbi1jaGFzZS1hY3F1aXJlcy1zdWJzdGFu=
dGlhbC1tYWpvcml0eS1vZi1hc3NldHMtYW5kLWFzc3VtZXMtY2VydGFpbi1saWFiaWxpdGllcy1=
vZi1maXJzdC1yZXB1YmxpYy1iYW5rLWNvbmZlcmVuY2UtY2FsbC0vSlBNb3JnYW5fQ2hhc2VfUH=
Jlc2VudGF0aW9uLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC100ff7f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> investor p=
resentation</a> touts both the =E2=80=9Chigh-quality portfolio=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0with a =E2=80=9Cstrong credit profile=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and also JPMorgan=E2=
=80=99s own =E2=80=9Ccomprehensive due diligence to support transaction ass=
umptions.=E2=80=9D JPMorgan did not need a loss-sharing agreement with the =
FDIC because it was worried that First Republic=E2=80=99s loans were toxic.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan needed a loss-sharing agreement to=C2=
=A0<em>improve the capital accounting for the deal</em>. I have, above, use=
d simple math =E2=80=94=C2=A0assets minus liabilities, equity divided by as=
sets =E2=80=94=C2=A0to describe bank capital, but actual bank capital requi=
rements are based on <em>risk-weighed assets</em>. Capital is a cushion des=
igned to protect a bank from losses, and a bank needs more capital against =
risky assets than it does against safe assets. A big pile of mortgages and =
commercial loans=C2=A0will get an=C2=A0<em>okay=C2=A0</em>risk weighting, b=
ut a big pile of mortgages and commercial loans=C2=A0<em>insured by the FDI=
C</em>=C2=A0will get a=C2=A0<em>better=C2=A0</em>risk weighting. If JPMorga=
n had just bought these loans outright, its capital ratios would have suffe=
red. But, it says, the =E2=80=9CFDIC loss share agreements reduce risk weig=
hting on covered loans,=E2=80=9D so=C2=A0its common equity tier 1 capital r=
atio will still be =E2=80=9Cconsistent with 1Q24 target of 13.5%.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On an <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL3N0b3JpZXMvUlRaRUFPR0pDRDIwP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZ=
WRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwMSZ1dG1fY2Ft=
cGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6229b461" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">analyst c=
all</a>=C2=A0this morning, JPMorgan Chief Financial Officer Jeremy Barnum d=
iscussed this point:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What I would say broadly is that g=
iven the nature of the portfolio and question, I think First Republic is ve=
ry well-known for very good credit discipline. As you point out, these are =
primarily rate marks. And therefore, the benefit of the loss share really i=
s the sort of enhancement to the RWA [<em>risk-weighted asset</em>]=C2=A0ri=
sk-weighting, which in turn is what makes these otherwise generally not ver=
y-high returning assets, in other words, prime jumbo mortgages primarily, a=
ctually quite attractive from a returns perspective. So the CET1 [<em>commo=
n equity tier 1 capital</em>] numbers fully incorporate the expected risk-w=
eighting of the RWA, and we'll leave it at that, I think.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A normal mortgage loan <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGF2aXNwb=
2xrLmNvbS9zaXRlcy9kZWZhdWx0L2ZpbGVzL3VwZGF0ZWRfYXByaWxfMjAxNV92aXN1YWxfbWVt=
b191c19iYXNlbF8zX2ZpbmFsX3J1bGUucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2573f756" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> gets about a 50% risk weight</a>, so at its 13.5% target capital rati=
o, JPMorgan would need to fund that mortgage with almost 7% equity capital.=
 <em>These</em> mortgages get about a 25% risk weight, meaning that JPMorga=
n can get away with half as much capital, which makes its return on equity =
from these mortgages much higher.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, by the way, a classic sort of financi=
al engineering, a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMTgtMDUtMjUvZXVyb3BlYW4tYmFua3MtZ2V0LWNyZWF0aXZlLXdpdGgtY2FwaXRhbC1yZWxpZW=
Y_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBcca82a4e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> capital relief trade</a>.=C2=A0You hav=
e a situation where the bank has loans that it thinks are very safe, but th=
e regulatory capital requirements treat them as kinda risky; the regulators=
 and the bank disagree on their risk. So the bank finds some well-funded th=
ird party that agrees with it that the loans are very safe, and buys very c=
heap insurance from that third party: The bank thinks the loans are safe,=
=C2=A0the third party agrees they=E2=80=99re safe, so the insurance premium=
 is low, and insuring the loans lowers their capital requirements. It=E2=80=
=99s just that, here, the regulator (the FDIC) is also selling JPMorgan the=
 insurance (for free). Everyone agrees that these loans are safe, but the c=
apital regulations treat them as risky. There is a trade to be done. With t=
he regulator.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For that matter, why does JPMorgan need to bor=
row $50 billion from the FDIC to do this deal? Why can=E2=80=99t it pay $60=
.6 billion upfront? The answer is not that it couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0scrape =
together the $60.6 billion in cash today; the answer is that JPMorgan, as a=
 big stable bank, needs to keep a lot of cash around in case=C2=A0<em>it=C2=
=A0</em>has a bank run, and spending so much cash on First Republic would n=
ot be a prudent use of liquidity. On the analyst call, Barnum described the=
 FDIC loan in these terms: =E2=80=9CThe deal also includes a $50 billion 5-=
year fixed-rate funding facility from the FDIC, which helps manage the ALM =
[<em>asset/liability management</em>] profile of the transaction, as well a=
s the liquidity consumption.=E2=80=9D First Republic had some long-term loa=
ns that it funded with short-term deposits, and look what happened to it. J=
PMorgan is going to fund those long-term loans with=C2=A0long-term borrowin=
g.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can see the levers here, the financial eng=
ineering. The FDIC=E2=80=99s goal here is to minimize the loss to its insur=
ance fund, to sell First Republic for roughly what it is worth. But its oth=
er goal is to make sure that the banking system is well capitalized, and se=
lling First Republic for 100% of its asset value doesn=E2=80=99t help with =
that goal; it just moves the capital hole somewhere else. The solution is s=
ome combination of:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell First Republic to a very-well-ca=
pitalized bank, one that can absorb the capital hole. =E2=80=9CFortress pri=
nciples position us to invest through cycles =E2=80=94=C2=A0organically and=
 inorganically,=E2=80=9D says JPMorgan=E2=80=99s presentation about the dea=
l; it has spent years bragging about its =E2=80=9Cfortress balance sheet,=
=E2=80=9D and that really does let it do deals like this. But this deal wil=
l bring down its capital ratios a bit; a well-capitalized bank that absorbs=
 an insolvent one will become a bit less well capitalized.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Give that bank a discount: JPMorg=
an is paying a bit more than 100% of the current market value of First Repu=
blic=E2=80=99s bonds and loans, but a bit less than 100% of the total value=
 of its assets. It will book a gain on the deal, which will help maintain i=
ts capital ratios.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Engineer the de=
al to optimize the regulatory treatment: If giving JPMorgan an FDIC guarant=
ee on some assets will lower its risk-weighted assets, you do that. If givi=
ng JPMorgan a long-term FDIC loan will improve its liquidity ratios, you do=
 that.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can to some extent trade off the discount =
against the engineering: Surely JPMorgan=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>have abso=
rbed First Republic with no loan from the FDIC (worse for its regulatory li=
quidity requirements) and no loss-sharing agreement (worse for its regulato=
ry capital ratios), but it would have paid less, which means that the FDIC =
would have paid more. But the FDIC did the math and concluded that the loan=
 and loss-sharing made for a better deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine going further. JPMorgan coul=
d have come to the FDIC and the Fed and said =E2=80=9Clook, we would like t=
o pay full value for these assets, but we have these pesky capital requirem=
ents. But you set the capital requirements; you could, you know,=C2=A0<em>w=
aive=C2=A0</em>them a bit. Let us ignore First Republic in calculating our =
capital ratios; then we won=E2=80=99t need as much capital to do the deal, =
and we can pay more.=E2=80=9D Something a=C2=A0<em>little</em>=C2=A0like th=
at happened in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/313=
39354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
MtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwNTAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB80a18dd8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  UBS Group AG=E2=80=99s deal</a> to buy Credit Sui=
sse Group AG in March: Swiss regulators, who insisted on the deal, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZmlubWEuY2gvZW4vbmV3cy8yMDIzLzAzLzIwMjMwMzE5LW1tLWNzLXVicy8/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBa7b3244c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> agreed to</a> =E2=80=9Cgrant appropriat=
e transitional periods=E2=80=9D for UBS to meet its capital requirements af=
ter the deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course you want to minimize that sort o=
f thing, because the goal here is not just to make sure that First Republic=
 opens for business today or to minimize the dollar losses to the FDIC=E2=
=80=99s insurance fund. The goal here is to restore confidence in the banki=
ng system, to send the message that the crisis is over and everything is fi=
xed. A rescue deal for First Republic that weakens the capital or liquidity=
 of its buyer is not a good solution. You don=E2=80=99t want to do too much=
 financial engineering; you don=E2=80=99t want to leave the buyer=C2=A0<em>=
technically=C2=A0</em>well capitalized but=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>in a m=
ore dangerous place. But a <em>little</em> engineering is fine.</p>
