<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">US CDS</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simple way to think about a credit default=
 swap is that it is insurance on a bond. If you own $1 million=C2=A0of the =
bonds of some company or government, you can buy $1 million of CDS to prote=
ct yourself; you pay some periodic insurance premium for this protection. I=
f the issuer defaults on its debt, you get made whole; you get your $1 mill=
ion back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When an issuer defaults on its debt, usually t=
he debt is worth=C2=A0<em>something:=C2=A0</em>A company will go bankrupt a=
nd pay back its bonds at 20 or 40 cents on the dollar or whatever, or a gov=
ernment will restructure its debt and give bondholders some value back. And=
 so the way CDS works is basically that, when an issuer defaults, the CDS p=
ays back 100 cents on the dollar=C2=A0<em>minus=C2=A0</em>the value of the =
bonds. If a company goes bankrupt and its bonds recover 37 cents on the dol=
lar, then its CDS will pay out 63 cents on the dollar. If you have $1 milli=
on of bonds plus $1 million of CDS, you will get back $370,000 on the bonds=
 and $630,000 on the CDS and be fully insured.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes this works simply enough: A company =
has one set of bonds, it defaults, they pay out 37 cents, the CDS pays the =
other 63 cents, easy. Sometimes, though, a company or government will have =
different bonds that get different recoveries that are all covered by the s=
ame CDS contract. The CDS will pay out one amount, set by an auction and mo=
re or less corresponding to the recovery of the=C2=A0<em>worst=C2=A0</em>(=
=E2=80=9Ccheapest-to-deliver=E2=80=9D) bond.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hre=
f=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And so if a company goes bankrupt and one bond gets 37 cents on t=
he dollar and another gets 41, the CDS will probably pay out about 63 cents=
 on the dollar, and if you had one of the 41-cent bonds and hedged with CDS=
 you will get back 104 cents on the dollar, great.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be clear, unlike in actual insurance, you d=
on=E2=80=99t need to own the bonds to buy CDS. If you want to bet against a=
 company=E2=80=99s credit, you can buy CDS on it, and then if it defaults y=
ou get the CDS payoff. (People get mad about this, but never mind; in finan=
cial markets buying CDS is a way to=C2=A0<em>short=C2=A0</em>bonds.) If=C2=
=A0the bonds pay off 37, then you get back 63; you never owned the bonds bu=
t that=E2=80=99s fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice that if you are a bond investor who bou=
ght CDS as a hedge, you don=E2=80=99t care very much about the bond recover=
y; if the recovery is X, you get X on the bonds and 1 - X on the CDS and it=
 doesn=E2=80=99t matter what X is. If you bought CDS to short the bonds, th=
ough, you want the bond recovery to be as low as possible, because you get =
paid 1 - X.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Where this becomes very fun is in the category=
 of trade that is sometimes loosely referred to as =E2=80=9Cmanufactured de=
faults.=E2=80=9D These trades go something like this. Some company needs mo=
ney. Some hedge fund owns a lot of CDS on the company.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-11" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; d=
isplay: inline-block;">
<span>[11]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The hedge fund goes to the company and says =E2=80=9Clook, it wil=
l help us out a lot if you default on your debt. Why don=E2=80=99t you just=
, like, miss the deadline for an interest payment by a week.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-12" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[12]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Then you will be in default and our CDS will trigger and we=E2=80=
=99ll get paid. Then you go back and make the interest payment and nobody c=
omplains too much; you won=E2=80=99t go bankrupt or anything. And then we=
=E2=80=99ll have all this money from our CDS payoff, and we=E2=80=99ll writ=
e you a big check, and you=E2=80=99ll have more money too.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The mechanics are a bit more complicated,=C2=
=A0and people =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTgvc2luZnVsLWRlcml2YXRpdmVzLWhhdmUtdGhlaXItdXNlcz9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwNTAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB6e9a8f86" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">even the pope</a>! =E2=80=94=C2=A0get mad abo=
ut this, but never mind that either. The point I want to make here is just =
that there is a flaw in this logic, which is that if you manufacture a defa=
ult at a company where=C2=A0<em>everything is otherwise fine</em>, the bond=
s=C2=A0<em>won=E2=80=99t lose much value</em>, and so the CDS won=E2=80=99t=
 pay off that much. The CDS will trigger, there=E2=80=99ll be an auction fo=
r the debt, people will be like =E2=80=9Cmeh this debt is fine,=E2=80=9D th=
e auction will clear at like 95 cents on the dollar, and the CDS will pay o=
ff like 5 cents.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there is a refinement on the manufactur=
ed-default trade, which is that you also have to find, or manufacture, a ba=
d=C2=A0<em>bond</em>. If some junk-rated-but-okay company has a lot of bond=
s that pay 12% interest and trade at 99 cents on the dollar, and it manufac=
tures a default, that doesn=E2=80=99t do its CDS holders much good. But if =
it has a 30-year bond with a 2% interest rate that trades at 20 cents on th=
e dollar, and<em>=C2=A0</em>it manufactures a default, then the CDS will pa=
y off 80.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-13" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[13]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every so often the US government thinks about =
defaulting on its debt for no particular reason; this is called the =E2=80=
=9Cdebt ceiling standoff.=E2=80=9D The somewhat surprising rule of thumb is=
 that when there is a debt ceiling standoff =E2=80=94=C2=A0when the US gove=
rnment starts thinking about defaulting on its debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0the pric=
e of US government debt goes=C2=A0<em>up</em>. The thinking is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A US government default would be a ba=
d destabilizing event in financial markets generally.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">When markets are bad and destabilized, there is a fligh=
t to quality; people want to buy safe assets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The safest assets are US government debt, so the price of US go=
vernment debt goes up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Even in a US government default</em>, US government debt will be safe, =
because the government has plenty of money and is defaulting for no particu=
lar reason, and it will quickly fix the default and start paying its debts =
again.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So a US debt default would lead to panic, but =
not actually any significant impairment on the payments of, like, 30-year T=
reasury bonds. Which means that the prices of those bonds will go up in the=
 panic.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can buy credit default swaps on US governm=
ent debt, but historically that has not been a great way to speculate on th=
e debt ceiling standoff: If the US government defaults, its bonds will=C2=
=A0trade to, like, 102 cents on the dollar, and your CDS might trigger but =
won=E2=80=99t pay much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that is the thinking from a long period of=
 declining interest rates, and now things have changed. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0Sujata Rao-Coverley, Denitsa Tsekova and Liz McCormick <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjgvYmV0cy1vZmZlcmluZy0yLTQ=
wMC1wYXlvdXQtb24tdXMtZGVmYXVsdC1sdXJlLWdyb3dpbmctY3Jvd2Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMT=
IzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjMwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB99=
14cb9a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">reported on Friday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In what is a traditionally moribund corner of =
Wall Street, speculators are piling into a bet that once seemed unthinkable=
: that the US government will default on its debts.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With the Treasury Department inching ever clos=
er to running out of cash =E2=80=94 most estimates give it another=C2=A0<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31339354.258432/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjEvZGVidC1jZWls=
aW5nLWFueGlldHktdHJhY2tlci13b3JyaWVzLWZ1ZWwtYmlsbC1jdXJ2ZS1kaXN0b3J0aW9uP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDA1MDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBb1c416b0" target=3D"_blank" title=3D"Debt-Ceiling Anxiety Tr=
acker: Worries Fuel Bill Curve Distortion" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">few months</a>=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 trading in the derivatives, known as credit-default swaps, =
is growing. The amount of money tied to the contracts, which will reward in=
vestors if the US misses any payments, has increased roughly eight-fold sin=
ce the start of the year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This isn=E2=80=99t the first time that a mini-=
mania around this trade has erupted. There were episodes back in 2011, 2013=
, and to a lesser extent 2021. But this time, it all feels a bit different.=
 =E2=80=A6 A quirk in the derivatives market means they can take advantage =
of the rock-bottom prices on long-term US bonds to juice gains on the contr=
acts should the US actually default. With some Treasuries recently trading =
below 60 cents on the dollar =E2=80=94 the result of the Federal Reserve=E2=
=80=99s rapid-fire series of interest-rate hikes =E2=80=94 the potential pa=
yout could exceed 2,400%, according to Bloomberg calculations.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Treasuries don=E2=80=99t trade below 60 cents =
on the dollar because people are worried about the credit risk of the US go=
vernment. Treasuries trade below 60 cents on the dollar because they are 30=
-year bonds issued in 2020 with interest rates of 1.25%, and now long-term =
interest rates are much higher.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-14" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[14]</span>
</a>=C2=A0If the US government defaulted this year, it is overwhelmingly li=
kely that holders of those bonds would get all of their money back, more or=
 less on schedule. But if the US government defaulted this year, credit def=
ault swaps would trigger, and those bonds would sell for about 60 cents on =
the dollar. Which means that the CDS could pay out a lot.</p>
